Professor was incredibly understanding (pandemic and personal). She cares about your mental health just as much as your work. She will check up on you if you have a missing assignment and she grades by rubric. Although I feel she could have used more intersectionality, she did use studies and we discussed race a few times. Interesting class!

Kate is literally such a sweet woman. I really enjoyed this class. She does assign a lot of reading but you don't really have to do all of them because she summarizes them in class. Nonetheless, I would recommend skimming them anyway. It's not a hard class to get an A in and I would recommend taking it.

Dale is very smart and eloquent. Unfortunately, to put it mildly, he is not a nice person. He has no qualms about putting you down in front of other students. And he has a very condescending tone. And he is an extremely poor advisor to his grad students. If you're thinking about working with him, proceed with caution. You've been warned. Good luck.
Dr. Woods is sweet, but she speaks SO slow and monotonous. The class environment is not engaging at all.
HE IS THE BEST!!!!!!!!!!!

This class was horribly boring. He tries to make it amusing but I constantly had to fight off sleep. Nice guy though. Approachable and always looking to help. But if you prefer a structured environment, look elsewhere.

Dr. Youngstrom was a great professor. I'm innately horrible at math, and with his help (his TA Andrew Freedman is really good too) I got an A in statistics! Always willing to help, and he obviously designs the class so you can get the highest grade possible. If you have to take PSYC 210, definitely take it with Youngstrom!
This dude is goofy as hell. He does his best to makes statistics interesting. Take his class if you get the chance. You'll actually learn the material without being bored to tears.

Dr. Youngstrom is one of the greatest professors I have ever had. He managed to make something as boring as statistics extremely fun! I would recommend this class to anyone who is a psychology major or who needs a statistics class!

I thoroughly enjoyed every aspect of this class. Obviously the trip to Perto Rico was an amazing experience! Additionally, I feel like this class taught me a lot about looking closer at the infrastructure around me and how it can be improved. I also really enjoyed the reading assignments and final project.
I dislike the downtime in lab but I'm not complaining about it because I just do homework.

the labs were a little to _figure it out yourself_ when it came to matlab and the PLC ladder logic concepts, the 2 page abstract seamed to not be much different from a full report but keep with it its a nice idea and i think it will keep going better as you use it and can know better what to tell people
The course had a very strict schedule of one asssignmwnt due at the beginning of every class and this was very convenient for remembering when to do homework
I really appreciate how quickly she answers emails, and how well she conveys her caring for our well being, and overall success in this class.

dr. is a very nice guy and he's passionate about this course he tried to light a fire under everyone's *** when the class was behind in work and i feel he did it in a good way not getting agitated or mad just making sure we knew as a class where we were at. i liked the figure it out by yourself element of the class as i think i work better with hands on items * Inappropriate words were found and removed from this response.

A small suggestion would be to remove certain projects, while specific examples are hard to think of at the moment, there were several cases where projects deadlines would appear to be far off and after a week would appear out of nowhere leading to many nights of cramming and less than ideal work. This was commonly caused by being focused on other deadlines that were coming up sooner.
The strengths of the course were the learning objectives and assignments because they were well prepared and very good input for our futures. I enjoyed reading the book we were assigned as well!

The class is very well organized and there are never any doubts for what is expected of us in the upcoming class and beyond. If there is a schedule change, we are notified of it immediately which gives us adequate time to prepare for the change.

The weekly meetings are not too engaging. Most of the time there were alumni speakers talking about their experiences in the mechanical engineering field. It was very helpful information, but hearing them talk for a class period got a little tiresome.
Having a sort of lab to just work solely on the project and meet with group members.

I feel like overall the ICAs kinda killed the course. We would never really get enough time to get the ICA done in class like it should be done and then we would have to do it in free time taking away from time to do our projects and overall think it hurt everyone in the course.
This course is good just how it is
The course felt sporadic and choppy. The work load was a lot more than I expected and felt meaningless. Â Â

I feel as the only weakness was the lack of clarification at times. Sometimes, I was just unsure when things were due or what was expected from me on certain assignments. I disliked the very often forum posts and readings. Though they could be helpful for understanding content little were they tied into the content or even mentioned in passing. I also just think at times it was a lot of reading overall. I would say if it was cut down to 1-2 articles or chapters a week that were mentioned in class that would be better.
This course could be improved by using a Moodle page for better organization. Overall, the course went well.

This is one of the most well structured and interesting courses as an incoming freshman at ONU. Based upon the limited number of other classes I have taken at ONU. The teaching style is phenomenal and one of the most well organized and mandated curriculum. It is apparent that the Professors want the students to be successful and practice many applicable engineering content. Prepares students for industry and teamwork. Dr. is a tremendous professor. One of the most organized professors at Ohio Northern and teaches students with passion.
it would be helpful to spend at least two days minimum on each chapter: the first day covering all of the rules, the second day actually working through the textbook problems
Try to get the grades back sooner if possible but otherwise I liked this course.

ONU struggles with sharing information to students about job opportunities/residencies. I am not saying they do not provide opportunities to meet but they provide no guidance to PHORcas, submitting transcripts (the instructions were missing VERY crucial information). I think this can fixed by having P6s talk to the P5s when we are coming back to boot camp. A simple breakout session to those who want to help would help the next class immensely. Lastly, I feel the relationship between the experiential office and the P6 classes needs to drastically improve. Consistent threats of grade dropping, failing rotations, and an overall adversarial relationship does not build a productive relationship/build prepared pharmacists. Students are scared in the first place for these rotations and ONU consistently threatening to drop grades or fail rotations does not help anyone. My suggestion is to have these conversations on a al level. I am not saying to have a one on one session with every student but those who are struggling might need help.

One single document with all the assignments/requirements, not several and copy and paste that same material into CORE. It seemed that older material/assignments from past years were on all different documents which made everything confusing and things have been copy and pasted but never updated.
This course could be improved by allowing revisions on all papers so that the students can obtain feedback and learn from their mistakes.
Professor is very knowledgeable about accounting and was able to spend lots of time helping us out with assignments

This class felt like a class where you got feedback from industry that said we should know certain things and then all of that got dumped into this class. Also the workload was something I would expect from a 4 credit hour class, but this was only 2. Grading was also extremely slow. At the time of writing this, i have been waiting for a grade and feedback on a report that was turned in over a month ago, and the feedback would be helpful for writing the next report which is due in two days.

This course could be improved by being slightly more descriptive in grading rubrics. I felt like a majority of the rubrics were very _loose_ in terms of instruction, and because of this my grade has suffered quite a bit. On assignments which I thought I did correctly my grade has been much lower than expected. I then have to take time out of my day to review the work with a TA and receive minimal points back.
Lots of visual examples

The strength was definitely the professor because without the professor explaining everything so well, I wouldn't have understood anything. I really enjoyed the ality that the professor gave off, everyone was in a good mood every time the professor talked. The book that we used was definitely the most effective for me because it really taught me how to do citations and taught me new things.

The biggest weakness of this course is how much time is spent listening and watching Dr. write. I am a rather visual learner, and I find it very difficult to listen to a single speak for an extended period of time. Apart from this, I feel the course was well put together, and I understand that it may be difficult to incorporate more hands-on or video activities into a professional ethics class.

I liked the books that we red for this class. I liked how he let us talk and then he would talk as well. It was like a conversation not a class, I really enjoyed that and everything that we did was real world things.
Professor Parker gives very fair exam questions and I ended up learning more information in this course than I thought I would at the beginning of the semester. I ended up really liking the course!
No need for improvement, I really enjoyed this class with Dr. as the instructor.

ally, I do not like the on your own projects and timeline. I just do a bad job at timing out my projects when there isn't a deadline. However, I do realize that this is how the course is designed and that in the real world, you have to learn to pace yourself.
I liked how when I walked into this class, I wasn't stressed out. It was a nice environment which was a change of pace.
I think it's just fine!
Gave a background and development into constructing a Senior Thesis

The strengths of this course was the lab allowed us to work with actual hardware on motor controls and then calculate what we were trying to find from what we learned in class or by simulation then compare the two results to see how similar they are. The teaching methodologies I found most effective was how he would design the homework's then when they were due he would have a quiz over the type of material which was on that homework's topics which helped me learn better.
Didn't like the talk through the notes method of teaching.
it was hard some days to get better grades and some of the time the TA's were unavailable for the majority of times that work for most people in the class.
Projects could have er time frames

I think that the groupwork is great, but there seems to be nothing I can do about group members who don't do enough. I also think that the teach-yourself method is dangerous because people who don't care just wont do it and probably wont remember it.
The strengths is that he knew what he was talking about and was able to respond to emails when a questions came up in a timely manner.
I cannot think of any weaknesses of this course at the moment, I loved this course!
I wish grades were posted more often as I am still currently waiting for a grade back on a speech I did a month ago.
I don't see anything that needs to be improved for this course.

I feel like what was asked for in the _memos_ where more detailed than needed for a memo. It also ran too much like a fluid mechanics or thermodynamics class and didn't feel like a lab. I would have instead learned/used more equipment than do calculations that I already do in my other classes.
Very good instructor with high intentions of his class
No weaknesses

I think the course is very good. Though the tests tend to be extremely dense with difficult information, it is all about the student's ability to retain that content. The biggest improvement I would have is more practice questions and group work with the professors to have quick explanations about content that is confusing.
No notable weaknesses were discovered during my time.

Controls in the Laplace domain is very abstract, but it was taught well with simple language and the lab was very helpful in seeing the actual application of what we did in lecture. I also like that there are conceptual questions on exams as it ensures students know the fundamentals and consequences of certain things.

This course could be improved by making sure quizzes open up at the end of course, having structors take at least 50 minutes so it doesn't feel pointless to come, changing the total point total to be larger than 100, and making the final not as impactful on students grades especially when they have not taken an exam all year.

I loved the hands-on aspect of this course and it was all like applicable experiments. I also enjoyed the fact that there really wasn't anything we did that wasted time or did just to do something. It was all a very intentional class and I appreciated that.
more timely on grading and more feedback on homework assignments.
Provide more opportunities for grades other than 3 writing assignments.

It was open and inviting for students to participate, he was very enthusiastic. A teaching method that we found most effective was when we actually went over the rules with questions relating to them such as Rule 12 and FRAP 4(a).
he just went over homeworks that we did and nothing else
The course was frustrating but for reasons out of the faculty's control.
I would like the textbook to have an online version, or the required readings to be scanned onto moodle
I think the weakness of the course is just how much of a load we are given. It kind of makes us feel like we don't want to do this work anymore
The strength of the course was the lab in tandem with the lecture. The material became easier to grasp from both seeing the analytical and practical aspects, and the two reinforced each other.
disliked how little time we spent covering each chapter; felt very fast passed without really determining what the law was
The homework feels unnecessary with the class. It was just busy work. Idk if I could tell you 1 homework assignment that actually felt like it improved my learning.

I think some things in the course were very productive and really furthered my education in my field (Arduinos, soldering). I liked the learn at your own pace type things, especially when I was actually interested in teaching myself.

The weaknesses of the course were the instructions for a few of the assignments. There wasn't anything in particular that I disliked. I did not find any of the methods ineffective that I can think of.
Perhaps consider reformatting the slides in someway, making sure enough writing prompts are given to re-express the ideas, but also allowing students to take pause and consider what is being said.
Many of the example problems in lecture felt rushed and were hard to keep up with writing notes and following the steps needed to solve problems.
Maybe just focus a little more on the stuff needed for an exam since, whether it should be the case or not, passing the class is the most important thing.

The sarcastic and sometimes rude comments on reports with little helpful info. The fact that it seems as if you are being judged every time you make a mistake. Lectures were like a boring lullaby that makes you wanna sleep as soon as you sit down.

This class provided on of the best experiences of my college career. While learning about infrastructure in another part of the world was very interesting, being able to travel there and experience it with such an amazing group of people made the class 10X more effective. All of the reading and videos helped broaden my horizons on the world and how different areas are built up. I learned an incredible amount about many different engineering topic and gained a phenomenal group a friends from the experiences. It not only was a great learning experience, but such a great social experience and gave me a greater passion for travel and helping people. This was challenging in a the perfect way, to help us think critically about the island and all the topics. Thank you for everything.
What I enjoyed was how professor was in depth about historical figures and events. What methodologies that worked great were the professor provided information but let us draw our own conclusions.
Maybe a tad too many projects to complete for an A in the course. I found it super hard just to get a B, but then again, it might be due to my dual majoring.

I really appricated that this class had a much more hands on teaching style it kept me much more nterested and engaged in the course matter. I really enjoyed how the proffessor would apply what we were being taught to real life situations and even have multiple demonstations/ labs to further emphasize the course material. His teaching style was a great change from the usual lecture heavy based courses and while lecture was still very important the proffessor made it more interactive and much less grueling than many other courses.

Not necessarily a weakness, but I think putting out that there is an online textbook version would be best as it is cheaper for a semester subscription than buying the physical book. With offering the online book I like having my laptop to take notes, but I understand why not.
More structure with more explanation to be able to get through the course. Keeping everyone close to the same place so we can seek help from our peers.
I thought the subject matter was interesting. Dr. put in an effort to be engaging and ask questions to try and ascertain everyone's understanding.
The memo reports seemed like a little overkill for the content we learned. Maybe we could try to do a 2-page abstract for one or two of the reports rather than a full report.

It really puts students down when the only communication we receive from our experiential office is an email telling us how unprofessional we are and how disappointed we are making ONU. I feel that at this point in rotations, if there are students who are consistently struggling with professionalism or other things, they should be reach out to individually and assisted. Speaking this way to the whole class when most of us get great feedback month after month can be really draining. Most of us are doing our best to improve professionally and make ONU look good, but it really brings down motivation when we get only negative/threatening communications and no encouragement. I understand that in the real world our bosses will probably also mostly provide criticism with little praise, because that's how the world works. I just firmly believe that if the experiential office is finding themselves continuously frustrated month after month with certain students' performances, they should begin reaching out to these students one-on-one to see what is going on and how to help them.

The weakness is how the information was portrayed. There are no specifics. It all done in a semi vague manner, where there are no real answers. There are only details that lead you to deciding if something is ethical within the eyes of a theory. The problem comes where the homework wants you to correctly identify if a situation is ethical or not. Many times, the wrong answer was stated due to the lack of definitiveness. I also dislike the way the professor stated directions. They were unclear in many ways, using very flamboyant language that alienated me from the material. These words also had specific definitions within the context of the situation. As a result, it was very hard to get to where the professor wanted. It also must be mentioned that the professor expects you to immediately think like an ethics major or professor. There is no correction in how you are thinking and how you get to the conclusion, he only cares about the correct answer. An example of this can be seen when one student was thinking about the level of giving different treatment, where the professor wanted the idea of going to a different professional. Instead of stating that the different part was correct, or stating that the student was too specific, the professor just said that the answer is not it. Giving no detail to why it was wrong, leaving us to our own devices to try and understand how the student was wrong.

I think the weakness of the course was the way we learned the material. I think that you should either have the students read the material and practice in class or teach the material and give homework. The homework certainly shouldn't be due the day that we review the material in class because if we don't understand it then we are forced to correct our homework in class, which leads to a rushed job. Also, if we do the homework before we clear up any misconceptions from reading the material and we aren't able to correct it before we turn in, then we won't have an actual representation on how much we understand the material, so we won't know if we need to review on certain topics.

Additionally, as I understand the purpose of the monthly emails of what to improve on, I must say that it is a bit of a confidence buster for most of us to read. I understand that those concerns are happening and I agree with the importance of addressing them, however I think it would be more helpful to the affected individuals and less hurtful to others to address the specific concerns with the specific students they are about. The weakness of this course was fundamentally divided into two parts that interlink: organization and applied skills. The outcomes of this course were confused to say the least. At many times it felt like a refresher of research methods. That in itself is not an entirely bad thing as a refresher of the skills discussed are useful for the purposes of writing a thesis. However, the application of these lessons felt lacking. Aside from being asked to submit work for our thesis we never really had the opportunity to work on them. The class felt that we were supposed to just absorb what we were being told and tact it onto our thesis. This left the class feeling more like research methods than an actual introduction to thesis writing. For those of us (most of the class) who already took reserach methods we really did not gain anything. Another weakness was the class was structured far more as a research methods class rather than a thesis. It felt that theory areas (often important for political science) were largely ignored in favor of purely quantitative work. It felt as though little attention was given to the wider design tools of a thesis. Another problem is that the professor often can come across as usurping student papers to transform it to their preferences against the wishes of the student.

I have three things: 1) Professor likes to make connections with other topics, which is lovely, but I think he assumes legal educations are more standardized than they are in practice. For example, one time he was trying to connect with a Civil Procedure principle that we were taught as _domicile,_ but he was looking for a different word (I don't remember much), so it looked like we just didn't know. Also, sometimes you forget things and then relearn them for the bar, and that's okay. I think the connection is good, but the expectations involved could be more flexible. 2) I really appreciate that Professor Baez tries to foster discussion, but I think sometimes he gets dissapointed if we don't come up with a bunch of different answers (like, recently we've been covering amortization and like-kind exchanges with number answers, and he'll want to put a bunch of numbers on the board, but we only come up with 2 or 3, and one of them is typically right, so I think he doesn't need to push so hard to get a diversity of answers. Although, teaching a class without a lot of response from students is also difficult). 3) Also, Professor Baez sometimes makes a mistake that I feel like is common with well-organized professors who rely on lots of class back-and-forth: Sometimes he's looking for an answer, and so he doesn't hear the student's whole answer, or quite register what they said. So, like, if he's looking for an answer but wants to talk about it one step at a time, but a student gives the full answer right away, he might latch on to the part he was looking for or recognizes first, and ask the student the next part. The student then assumes that part of what they said was wrong and has to search for another answer, and it feels awkward. But I guess I don't know how avoidable that really is, and its definitely not the end of the world.

My biggest complaint about this course was a lack of consistency. Maybe it was a result of inconsistency from the city of Kenton. Maybe it was a result of the flexibility provided for students to choose their own routes and have completely different design processes. Regardless of the reason, it seemed like the advisors were often on different pages when it came to expectations for their capstone group. I was told that faculty from the civil department met once a week and most weeks held a discussion about this capstone course. If this was indeed the case, you would think that the expectations would be similar and only differ as a result of the different goals and design processes of each capstone group. Instead, I often got the impression that each advisor had very different expectations for their capstone group when it came time to have advisor meetings or present for a PRB. A little more consistency throughout the year would have been much less confusing and possibly even yielded better results from the capstone groups.

This course was very poorly executed. 1.) The course followed the flipped classroom methodology, but why? The entire course from day one was set up so that the responsibility of getting and digesting the material was placed squarely on the student (The flipped classroom methodology) and class time was only used for review of what the student should have taught themselves (in some cases in relatively shallow detail relative the level presented in the chapter or needed for the HW) and reviewing the homework if there were specific questions that someone had. I'm unsure why this approach was taken as it put a lot of work on the student to get and digest the information in addition to doing the immense amount of homework assigned almost every class (More on this in another section). To be frank, if I was interested in the topic of logic, I could have purchased the textbook and worked through it in my spare time and gotten an equivalent if not better education than I did by taking this course (As this was essentially all the course was), with the added benefit of getting to choose the amount of work I did or was needed to understand a given topic. 2.) Far too much homework In total, we were assigned 1,179 required problems for homework throughout the course, which correlates to an average of 84.21 problems per week (excluding weeks 9 and 14 which were midterms and break respectively), where the max assigned in a single week was 159 problems. This workload is further compounded by the fact that the chapter readings were assigned to be done by the student before each class in addition to all quizzes being done outside of class (To his credit, when the problems per week are graphed, a decline can be noticed in correlation to when quizzes are assigned). It is my understanding that the professor was approached by several students saying that the workload was a little intense and asking for him to consider reducing it, to which he said that he would. The workload was never reduced. I understand that mastery requires practice, but at what point does practice become beating a dead horse? The defense will be that if there were a lot of questions then they were short, but how this is simply not the case, and even if it were, there is still a non-trivial amount of time associated with doing them in addition to the other responsibilities of the class. 3.) Poor use of class time This was touched on some in the previous sections but class time ideally should have been used to lecture over the material that was expected to be learned by the student in enough depth that the homework was doable (rather than relying on the student to essentially teach it to themselves) and for quizzes (If they're take-home, homework should have been paused) and exams (Ideally would have fit into 1 class period but not overly problematic that they didn't). These problems ultimately lead to not reading the chapters in depth like I had in the beginning and only skimming them to answer specific questions, trying to get the homework done as quickly as possible as I viewed it as a chore once I got past the point of feeling like it was sufficient to learn the material (typically happened in 7 to 12 questions), and not being overly motivated to go to class (typically only 4 or 5 people regularly showed up to class out of a class of 9 or so) as I felt that I wouldn't gain much from the shallow coverage of the material that would be offered after doing the 20-50 questions of homework or that I should instead use that time to get caught up on homework I had fallen behind on.

Like, the answers could have to do with civil liability, federal taxes, management ease, or be an answer as general as _for the money,_ and I don't know that there's a good way to indicate what exactly you're looking for when you ask those kinds of broad questions.

Although we are aware we represent ONU, we are mainly focused on enhancing our individual education and professionalism at this point. Writing emails to our class in a way that blames us for making ONU look bad and only pointing out the negative things does not make us want to do better or improve. In addition, the messages do not need to be sent out to our preceptors. The grading system is confusing to preceptors and its awkward for students to have to explain to the preceptor how to override the grade and change it to one that the preceptor wants to give. Less Homework: If mastery is a big concern, utilize moodle quizzes that are maybe 5 - 10 questions as homework, and if the student scores less than some threshold percentage have them be assigned another 5 - 10 problems.
